 a guiding idea, question, or mantra that has helped you shape it?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAs I was working on the issue I found myself thinking a lot about all the things in British culture that had shaped my style, my sense of humor, and my way of seeing the world, everything from soccer, to rave culture, to the royals. It all came into sharp focus for me maybe because I’d been away from the UK for 20 years. The bigger question I kept coming back to from a fashion perspective was this idea of the modern British eccentric and what that means now. I think twigs embodies that spirit quite perfectly.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat has surprised you most about being back in the British fashion scene? How has it changed from when you last lived in the UK?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIt’s funny because if there’s one thing I’ve kept up with over the years in the UK, it’s the fashion scene. So much of what I like to wear every day is by British designers or creative directors, the likes of Martine Rose, Wales Bonner, Simone Rocha, and Molly Goddard. I think it’s changed enormously over the years. In fact, it’s been so encouraging to see a new generation coming up more recently. Supriya Lele and Jawara Alleyene are two designers I’m particularly excited about. Both of their brands are featured in the cover story on FKA twigs. It was important to me that the clothes she wore spoke to this new crop of local fashion talent.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFavorite British guilty pleasure to have back in your life?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI have a killer sweet tooth, so I’m happy to have all the British desserts back in my life, including banoffee pie.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e","publishedDate":"2024-03-25T04:00:00.000Z","isFeatured":false,"isHidden":false,"tag":null,"createdAt":"2024-03-25T18:57:09.162Z","updatedAt":"2024-04-19T22:28:04.771Z","publishedAt":"2024-03-25T18:57:10.062Z","locale":"en