igital Operation Lead Tristan Xiang discusses Lunar New Year, the growth of the brand in the Chinese market and what we can expect in 2024.","text":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTell us a little bit about yourself. How did you find your way to Condé Nast?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI'm from Zhejiang province in China. I graduated with a degree in computer science but yet ended up in the fashion industry, which was a very interesting experience. I started working as a freelancer with Condé Nast and later joined the company. The editor I was working with at that time told me there was a headcount, asking me if I wanted to give it a try, and without hesitation I immediately said, \"No matter what, I'm in!\" At that time, China's new media landscape was changing rapidly, and as a member of Vogue's new media, I was in the line with the train of the ages.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow do you describe your job to friends and family?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI always tell my family members that Condé Nast is my second home and they couldn’t agree more.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI started working at Condé Nast shortly after graduating from college and it's been almost ten years since then. I've been here for almost my entire career, so it's really an irreplaceable sense of belonging. Everyone in my family knows that I work for Vogue (The Fashion Bible). Vogue China observes culture through the lens of fashion, looks at the world today and uses the best photo, video and text production to convey our values to readers. New media is also a very important part of this and I think we are doing something amazing together.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLunar New Year is approaching soon, what does this holiday mean to you and how do you plan to celebrate?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eMy family's tradition is that the entire extended family stays together for the Lunar New Year. It's a very high-quality time to spend together as a family. So basically, the entire holiday season is filled with family visits, with all the relatives going around and paying New Year's greetings to each other. My parents cook very well, so my stomach will always be full during the New Year.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eAnother recreational activity is playing mahjong, it's kind of a family tradition and we all participate in. But the moment I look forward to the most is New Year's Eve, my parents will put an auspicious red envelope under my pillow and a letter with their thoughts on the year for me and what they want to say, kinda cliché but it’s romantic and really touching.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eReflecting on this past year, what is a project that you worked on that you are most proud of?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThe projects I worked on in 2023 are Vogue Open Casting, Vogue film, Vogue Craftsmanship Project, Vogue China Fashion Fund and Vogue Forces of Fashion makes its debut in Shanghai, China. It feels like I've done so many projects this year. The project I’m most proud of would be Vogue Open Casting. In 2021, based on Vogue’s essential role in launching and growing talent’s careers, Vogue China holds an annual open casting call – for new faces of all ages and backgrounds. In 2023, for the first time, Vogue open casting went global, more than 1,054,000 \"votes\" were cast on new faces' \"comp card\" profiles. Meanwhile, our global call received more than 77,000 entries, which is really inspiring.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYou have been part of big tentpole events and moments for Vogue China such as Forces of Fashion. Can you tell us about the impact of the event in the market and how it contributes to the growth of Vogue China.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eNowadays, it's important to capture the attention of the public and the market while maintaining a high level of creativity on a daily basis. The big tentpole events are such highlights through which we connect almost all of our partners - the most influential celebrities, supermodels, photographers, brand clients and readers that Vogue China works with, and it becomes an important program for us.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eIt was also an opportunity to showcase the results of our major projects, such as the aforementioned projects, at the big tentpole events, giving the public and the market a more comprehensive view of the “Vogue China Universe.” This is also reflected in the data, as each big tentpole event generates a huge amount of exposure, measured in billions of dollars, with a high level of social media discussion and engagement, and a significant increase in followers.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYou also lead digital channels for the brand. What is something that you are currently working on that will help lead with the progression of those channels?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eEverything is changing so fast in China. There are so many digital/social media platforms in China and the environment is changing so fast that we need to keep an eye on the content and operation strategies of different social media platforms. We keep in touch with the official staff of all the platforms for a long time and with high frequency.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eIn terms of content, in addition to the content produced by Vogue digital itself, I will also work with other editorial teams at Vogue China to continue to create better IPs that are more engaging for our readers. New media is the most intuitive and timely way to synchronize with readers' feedback, so I will also work with other teams such as the consumer team and the digital team to analyze readers' data and profiles more accurately as support. We also need to focus on what's happening on social media, so my friends love to talk to me about what's going on and they are all surprised about how I know everything. I say, “Because I'm doing new media.”\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat can we expect to see from the brand in 2024?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e2024 continues to be a challenging and exciting year. We will continue to do Vogue China’s influential annual projects this year and I believe it will be more mature. At the same time, more projects will arrive, such as Vogue House, which will be launched in 2024. As our Vogue China audience seeks to be more immersed in the brand, we will “come home” to Beijing in the spring 2024 to a standalone house in Beijing with a history to match Vogue’s 131-year legacy.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThis is where our members enter Vogue’s world, brought to life off the page, an ever-evolving curation of culture and offline storytelling through the lens of fashion.Vogue House Beijing is a world-first, always-on offline destination for our engaged community. I'm looking forward to being able to officially see it. In the meantime, I'm looking forward to more changes happening in the digital world!\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eFinally, I wish you all a happy new year!\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","publishedDate":"2024-01-15T00:00:00.000Z","isFeatured":false,"isHidden":false,"tag":null,"createdAt":"2024-01-16T12:19:21.064Z","updatedAt":"2024-01-16T12:34:36.873Z","publishedAt":"2024-01-16T12:19:27.044Z","locale":"en","Image":{"data":{"id":5035,"attributes":{"name":"Untitled design (8).jpg","alternativeText":null,"caption":null,"width":1920,"height":1080,"formats":{"large":{"ext":".jpg","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/large_Untitled_design_8_dddd7cd8e9.jpg","hash":"large_Untitled_design_8_dddd7cd8e9","mime":"image/jpeg","name":"large_Untitled design (8).jpg","path":null,"size":38.69,"width":1000,"height":563},"small":{"ext":".jpg","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/small_Untitled_design_8_dddd7cd8e9.jpg","hash":"small_Untitled_design_8_dddd7cd8e9","mime":"image/jpeg","name":"small_Untitled design (8).jpg","path":null,"size":13.18,"width":500,"height":281},"medium":{"ext":".jpg","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/medium_Untitled_design_8_dddd7cd8e9.jpg","hash":"medium_Untitled_design_8_dddd7cd8e9","mime":"image/jpeg","name":"medium_Untitled design (8).jpg","path":null,"size":24.47,"width":750,"height":422},"thumbnail":{"ext":".jpg","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/thumbnail_Untitled_design_8_dddd7cd8e9.jpg","hash":"thumbnail_Untitled_design_8_dddd7cd8e9","mime":"image/jpeg","name":"thumbnail_Untitled design (8).jpg","path":null,"size":4.8,"width":245,"height":138}},"hash":"Untitled_design_8_dddd7cd8e9","ext":".jpg","mime":"image/jpeg","size":101.62,"url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/Untitled_design_8_dddd7cd8e9.jpg","previewUrl":null,"provider":"aws-s3","provider_metadata":null,"createdAt":"2024-01-16T12:17:43.099Z","updatedAt":"2024-01-16T12:17:43.099Z"}}},"tags":[]},{"id":5004,"Title":"We Are Condé Nast: Nicolas Milon","SEOTitle":null,"SEODescription":null,"slug":"we-are-conde-nast-nicolas-milon","category":"people","summary":"AD France Editor Nicolas Milon discusses his initiative ‘Small Spaces,’ the expansion of the feature in other markets and his favorite piece of architecture.","text":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTell us a little bit about yourself. How did you find your way to Condé Nast?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eAfter two courses, audiovisual then communication, I worked in cinema. But literary at heart, I missed writing. Afterwards, I joined advertising then communications before joining the press in 2014. I joined Condé Nast in 2015, first as a contributor for GQ and Vanity Fair and joined the editorial team of AD in 2018. When I was a child, I recalled wanting to be an architect. I have never been so close to the work of architects and interior designers. It’s an irony that I enjoy every day!\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow do you describe your job to friends and family?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI am a journalist and writer. I write about architectural projects, design pieces, major events in the world of architecture and design. In short, I put into words what others have imagined and achieved. They tell me about their beautiful projects and I transcribe the journey of their inspiration and what led to their realization. Writing is what I love doing and what I do best. Listening to talented and passionate people talk about their projects is a chance and I am never tired of it. Behind the smallest project, such as a 20 square meter apartment to renovate, there is an extensive thought process and countless variables. I am always in awe of the intelligence of creative thinking. So I like to communicate it to others.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYou initiated a format\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.admagazine.fr/search?q=SMALL+SPACES\u0026amp;sort=publishdate+desc\"\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003cu\u003e‘Small Spaces,’\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e which inspired other markets to incorporate it as well. Can you tell us a little bit more about the feature and how it all started.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eWe originated the idea of this format during the pandemic. It quickly became successful because the concept is clear: we can create small surfaces as beautiful as large ones. The wow effect can be a luxury of decoration or great ingenuity in the use of each square meter. The idea is that we can make it small and pretty by playing with materials, tones, contrasts, by daring and not being afraid. And that makes a difference.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow do you work with the other markets to ensure ‘Small Spaces’ is cohesive?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThis is a section that has always worked very well in France. We shared it with the European AD’s with the same success then the global markets became interested in it with good results as well. What a surprise to see small syndicated spaces in the United States and also in Mexico! Our rule: ideas, style and unparalleled production, even for a studio apartment. This seems to be understood throughout the world and each country now offers its creations of small spaces that we organize together like home tours! For the most impact, this year, we created a video format which is also very successful. Even if the success of this section might have to do with the difficulty of finding accommodation in large apartments or houses – all over the world.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYou have written articles from small to large homes in Paris, the Hamptons, Stockholm and more to renovation and expansion at the Dior flagship in Paris. What is your favorite piece of architecture? Why?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI like when architecture slips into a past creation. The work of Ieoh Ming Pei at the Louvre, Norman Foster at the British Museum or more recently Tadao Ando at the Bourse de Commerce in Paris are examples of understanding the existing and its history to better take the building elsewhere, further and project it into the future. Also among them is the Battersea Power Station in London, restored by WilkinsonEyre. In another approach, that of sustainable and innovative design, I would cite the\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/richard-gilder-center\"\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eRichard Gilder Center for Science, Education and Innovation\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e designed by Jeanne Gang in New York, whose work I greatly admire.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWho is your favorite designer, architect or artist? Why?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThe Memphis movement, which knew how to take the opposite view, took the design world by surprise and dared a rebirth of modernism rather than a rereading. I like the art of counter-attack when it is successful. I also like the work of Max Lamb and Vincenzo de Cotiis. In another spirit, Dimorestudio and more recently Hugo Toro handle the mixture of materials, patterns and colors like no others.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIn your opinion, what area or region has the best architecture? What do you like about it?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eFor the last two years I have been receiving more and more exciting projects from Poland. I discussed it before during summer with a young Franco-Polish designer, and she confirmed to me that something is happening in Poland — an energy, and an emulation. The launch of AD Poland, early October was a resounding confirmation. There is an ecosystem in the country of architects, designers, photographers and artistic directors behind magnificent projects with magnificent ideas excellently executed.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.admagazine.fr/article/studio-33-m2-chic-subtil-vintage\"\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eArchitects Dawid Konieczny\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e,\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.admagazine.fr/article/une-maison-en-bois-a-lesprit-libre-dans-la-foret\"\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eDobrowolska Studio\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e or\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.admagazine.fr/article/un-petit-appartement-au-style-classique-calme-et-relaxant\"\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eLa Folie Studio\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e are doing very exciting work. Mood Authors is an excellent photographer too, just to name a few.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","publishedDate":"2023-12-18T00:00:00.000Z","isFeatured":false,"isHidden":false,"tag":null,"createdAt":"2023-12-18T15:23:55.281Z","updatedAt":"2023-12-18T15:24:21.495Z","publishedAt":"2023-12-18T15:24:19.412Z","locale":"en","Image":{"data":{"id":4991,"attributes":{"name":"Untitled design (22) copy.png","alternativeText":null,"caption":null,"width":1920,"height":1080,"formats":{"large":{"ext":".png","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/large_Untitled_design_22_copy_3b5611f786.png","hash":"large_Untitled_design_22_copy_3b5611f786","mime":"image/png","name":"large_Untitled design (22) copy.png","path":null,"size":486.98,"width":1000,"he