a music journalist from the very minute that I learned that was an actual job that people had. In college, I interned at\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003eThe Village Voice\u003c/i\u003e and other publications, and started freelance writing for a variety of outlets, including Pitchfork. In 2005, Pitchfork’s founder, Ryan Schreiber, asked me if I wanted to move to Chicago to head up Pitchfork’s recently launched news section. I ran the news section until 2019, when I became Managing Editor. Earlier this year, I became Executive Editor.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow do you describe your job to friends and family?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI oversee the day to day operation of our website, making sure that everything that’s supposed to get published shows up when it’s supposed to show up. I also get to listen to music all day long, and then argue about it.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitchfork just released its best songs and albums of 2023. Could you tell us a little bit about the process of curating those lists?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eIt’s a very long, involved process that begins at the end of September. Over a hundred staff members and freelance contributors vote in two rounds of polls, and the results are whittled down into our final lists by our senior editors. We do a lot of group listening and even more debating on Slack and in meetings about what should and shouldn’t make the lists, and what order it all should be in.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYou have been with Pitchfork since 2005, how would you describe the best of songs/albums lists changing over the almost-near decade?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThe lists have become more wide-ranging and diverse, both in terms of the artists and styles of music that appear on them as well as the writers that compose the blurbs accompanying each entry.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat was your favorite song and album from the lists?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eIt was all about Olivia Rodrigo this year for me, so I’d have to say her song “Get Him Back!” and her album\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003eGUTS\u003c/i\u003e.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWere there any surprises or unexpected entries that stood out to you?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eIt was surprising how SZA’s album\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003eSOS\u003c/i\u003e maintained its Album of the Year status pretty much from the day it was released. (Yes, technically that was in December 2022, but it came out after our 2022 lists were published, so it counts!) But its power just couldn’t be denied. And of course, nobody was expecting Andre 3000 from Outkast to release an album of wordless ambient flute jazz, let alone that said album would be good enough to be included on our Best Albums list!\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat is your favorite part about compiling Pitchfork’s end-of-year lists?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThe process of debating what should be on the lists, and what order they should be in, is extremely fun. As is catching up on everything I missed from throughout the year.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWere there any notable trends or themes in the music landscape this year, as reflected in Pitchfork’s selections?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI think the most notable trend across our lists is the overall breakdown of strict genre boundaries, a process that has become accelerated with the rise of streaming services making it easy for anyone to access pretty much the entire history of recorded music with the click of a button. Take our number one album, SZA’s\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003eSOS\u003c/i\u003e, and our number one song, Lana Del Rey’s “A\u0026amp;W,” for example. SZA’s album contains R\u0026amp;B songs and punk songs and rap songs and pure pop songs. And “A\u0026amp;W” begins as a gentle acoustic ballad before the music completely switches and Lana starts rapping over a dance beat. So many of our favorite releases this year simply refused to be boxed into one specific style.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","publishedDate":"2023-12-11T00:00:00.000Z","isFeatured":false,"isHidden":false,"tag":null,"createdAt":"2023-12-11T16:00:53.718Z","updatedAt":"2023-12-11T16:01:35.276Z","publishedAt":"2023-12-11T16:01:32.501Z","locale":"en","Image":{"data":{"id":4859,"attributes":{"name":"Amy Phillips.jpg","alternativeText":null,"caption":null,"width":1920,"height":1080,"formats":{"large":{"ext":".jpg","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/large_Amy_Phillips_6afcd8eaa4.jpg","hash":"large_Amy_Phillips_6afcd8eaa4","mime":"image/jpeg","name":"large_Amy Phillips.jpg","path":null,"size":24.7,"width":1000,"height":563},"small":{"ext":".jpg","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/small_Amy_Phillips_6afcd8eaa4.jpg","hash":"small_Amy_Phillips_6afcd8eaa4","mime":"image/jpeg","name":"small_Amy Phillips.jpg","path":null,"size":7.45,"width":500,"height":281},"medium":{"ext":".jpg","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/medium_Amy_Phillips_6afcd8eaa4.jpg","hash":"medium_Amy_Phillips_6afcd8eaa4","mime":"image/jpeg","name":"medium_Amy Phillips.jpg","path":null,"size":14.18,"width":750,"height":422},"thumbnail":{"ext":".jpg","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/thumbnail_Amy_Phillips_6afcd8eaa4.jpg","hash":"thumbnail_Amy_Phillips_6afcd8eaa4","mime":"image/jpeg","name":"thumbnail_Amy Phillips.jpg","path":null,"size":2.79,"width":245,"height":138}},"hash":"Amy_Phillips_6afcd8eaa4","ext":".jpg","mime":"image/jpeg","size":90.24,"url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/Amy_Phillips_6afcd8eaa4.jpg","previewUrl":null,"provider":"aws-s3","provider_metadata":null,"createdAt":"2023-12-11T15:59:39.439Z","updatedAt":"2023-12-11T15:59:39.439Z"}}},"tags":[]},{"id":4999,"Title":"We Are Condé Nast: Maria Streshinsky","SEOTitle":null,"SEODescription":null,"slug":"we-are-conde-nast-maria-streshinsky","category":"people","summary":"WIRED’s Executive Editor for Features, Maria Steshinsky discusses WIRED’s 30th anniversary, where she hopes to see the brand 30 years from now and her favorite WIRED stories.","text":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTell us about your role at WIRED.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI’ve been so lucky at WIRED. In the beginning, I was a feature editor, and I loved that work. When Rob Capps left, he and Nick Thompson offered me the job of running the print magazine. Amazing. Then, a few years ago, a few of us rebuilt the features team to be digital-first, which was so much fun to do! So, now I just like to say, I oversee the features team, and (with our truly talented design and photo department) we also have the good fortune to be able to deliver a handful of our best digital-first features to subscribers in print form.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat has kept you at WIRED for 7 years?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThe staff. For sure. This is going to sound repetitive, but I get to work with such talented, thoughtful people. It happens all the time: Some member of the team will get excited about an idea, and it becomes infectious. That’s why I’ve stayed. That, and the fact that technology has continued to affect our lives deeply and dramatically, in good and, unfortunately, very bad ways that need to be unpacked. It feels important to stay on top of that story; to highlight the human side of the industry.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWIRED’s 30th Anniversary is approaching. Reflecting on those 30 years–and on your time here in particular–can you share some of the ways the brand has evolved?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eWell, our founders had a famously optimistic stance on the digital revolution—that it was this outsider force that was going to upend all these stale hierarchies. They weren't wrong, in a lot of ways, but tech isn't the outsider anymore. So the publication has evolved to be sure we're looking at all the power the tech establishment has gained, and the people wielding it. In the last few years–since I have been here–we have wanted to focus on how all this stuff, this money, this computing power, these breakthroughs, affect everyday people. I’d add to that, we also used to take more of a try-anything approach, do random, fun, crazy stunts. WIRED used to do a segment called “Most Dangerous Object in the Office.” Some of those old videos are hilarious. “Almost Impossible” was another. And Angry Nerd. I do miss some of those. A lot of those in fact. And, to be fair, we are talking about what to bring back!\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAre there any throughlines between WIRED’s mission in the early days and its mission now?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eWIRED was considered pretty out there when it started. “This thing called the internet is coming and will change your life!” Well, here we are. The thing is, we do still think, despite very serious problems—like how tech companies have exploited the worst of human nature—technology has and will do great things for human kind. We can’t fix our climate problems without it now. We can’t solve things like widespread disease without it.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat do you hope to see from WIRED in the next 30 years?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eSo many things: I hope the publication can continue to bring on elegant thinkers, who are terrific storytellers, who can—in any future medium that makes sense—deliver the smartest news. And the most thoughtful, relatable, touching, fun stories. And as I’ve said, stories that hold technology companies to account when their products lead to harm. I’m worried about the state of reading, especially longer stories, these days. So I’d love for us to be flexible, and play with form—to inform and delight audiences wherever they are.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIs there a WIRED story you’re most proud to have worked on?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThis will sound cliche, but it’s hard to pick just one. Being able to simply read any Andy Greenberg feature is a joy. I mean, his most recent—the full, exclusive story of the internet-crashing Mirai hack—was so, so good. Lauren Goode wrote a personal piece a few years ago about digital “photo memories” and how they can keep opening wounds. I hold that story up as an example to other writers. Lauren figured out the tech origins of photo memories, and then she went to the companies who built them to ask how, or if, they think about the downsides. It was a deft combination of a personal story that illuminated the human consequences of unthinking product development. Add to that, I’ve been able to work on super fun Jason Kehe, Jason Parham, Virginia Heffernan columns and stories. I just love seeing staff writers shine at features. And a great rough draft from a talented freelancer. I’m really lucky.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","publishedDate":"2023-12-04T00:00:00.000Z","isFeatured":false,"isHidden":false,"tag":null,"createdAt":"2023-12-04T13:20:40.517Z","updatedAt":"2023-12-04T13:20:44.425Z","publishedAt":"2023-12-04T13:20:44.420Z","locale":"en","Image":{"data":{"id":4824,"attributes":{"name":"Screenshot 2023-12-04 at 11.41.27.png","alternativeText":null,"caption":null,"width":868,"height":870,"formats":{"small":{"ext":".png","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/small_Screenshot_2023_12_04_at_11_41_27_2eb999c5f3.png","hash":"small_Screenshot_2023_12_04_at_11_41_27_2eb999c5f3","mime":"image/png","name":"small_Screenshot 2023-12-04 at 11.41.27.png","path":null,"size":324.11,"width":499,"height":500},"medium":{"ext":".png","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/medium_Screenshot_2023_12_04_at_11_41_27_2eb999c5f3.png","hash":"medium_Screenshot_2023_12_04_at_11_41_27_2eb999c5f3","mime":"image/png","name":"medium_Screenshot 2023-12-04 at 11.41.27.png","path":null,"size":692.6,"width":748,"height":750},"thumbnail":{"ext":".png","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/thumbnail_Screenshot_2023_12_04_at_11_41_27_2eb999c5f3.png","hash":"thumbnail_Screenshot_2023_12_04_at_11_41_27_2eb999c5f3","mime":"image/png","name":"thumbnail_Screenshot 2023-12-04 at 11.41.27.png","path":null,"size":38.13,"width":156,"height":156}},"hash":"Screenshot_2023_12_04_at_11_41_27_2eb999c5f3","ext":".png","mime":"image/png","size":228.54,"url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/Screenshot_2023_12_04_at_11_41_27_2eb999c5f3.png","previewUrl":null,"provider":"aws-s3","provider_metadata":null,"createdAt":"2023-12-04T13:20:08.089Z","updatedAt":"2023-12-04T13:20:08.089Z"}}},"tags":[]},{"id":4995,"Title":"We Are Condé Nast: Chiara Oltolini","SEOTitle":null,"SEODescription":null,"slug":null,"category":"people","summary":null,"text":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTell us a little bit about yourself. How did you find your way to Condé Nast?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI attended journalism school from 2006 to 2008\u0026nbsp; where I studied the interviews and stories of Vanity Fair Italia; they were a model to aspire to, in particular those by Paola Jacobbi, Silvia Nucini and Marco De Martino. The magazine was considered the place to be, I don't remember a single classmate who didn't want to be part of it.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThe first time I set foot in Condé Nast was through an internship at Glamour. I read the advert in the magazine and applied. I ultimately spent ten years there before moving to WIRED for two years, during which I saw firsthand the power of the WIRED Next Fest, the free festival dedicated to innovation, technology, science and culture. In the summer of 2021, Simone Marchetti called me to Vanity Fair — it was a bit like returning to journalism school while at the same time achieving a major goal.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow do you describe your job to friends and family?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eTo my brother and my peers, I am responsible for the entertainment section, which encompasses the world of cinema, TV series, music and literature. The word that comes to some people’s minds is ‘culture.’ More specifically, along with management, I select who should be on the cover and those to dedicate space to within the magazine or on the website. I often interview them myself, or I choose the best-suited journalist. I essentially \"cook\" the piece; I pass it on, and if need be, adapt the language to the format of Vanity Fair Italia, giving it a title and a summary. I also take care of organizing Vanity Fair Stories, a large-scale event that’s open to the public where we bring the featured talent in the magazine onto the stage.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eFor the rest of my family, there’s the short and simplified version: I interview actors, singers and writers. Generally, it’s the Hollywood stars who spark the curiosity of my aunts.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eVanity Fair Stories, the largest Vanity Fair event open to the public, was just held in Milan on November 25 and 26. What was your role in organizing the event, from conception to execution?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThe best word to describe my role in the organization of Vanity Fair Stories is curator. I select the guests to be involved, I contact them, work with them on the performance or the themes to bring to the stage, and I build the schedule. I work closely with the event director, and I also go on stage because the exchange with the artists is the best part.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat were some of your favorite takeaways from the event?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI curated the last three editions of Vanity Fair Stories and there are two moments that moved me the most.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThe first was in 2022, when I was on stage with Maria Schrader, director of the acclaimed Netflix series “Unorthodox” and the film “She Said” based on the courageous investigation by New York Times reporters Jodi Kantor and Megan Twohey who opened the Pandora's box of harassment in Hollywood. In the darkness of the Giorgio Gaber Lyric Theater in Milan, with a calm voice and a peaceful yet determined gaze, she told me: “I was 23 years old, he was several years older. I was terribly uncomfortable, he was aggressive in his gestures.\" She had never before told what happened to her at the beginning of her career. She handed it over to me and to Vanity Fair and from there on, I understood how intimate a stage can be.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThe second moment was at the 2023 edition, so on November 25th, I was on stage with Levante, the Italian singer-songwriter and writer. That morning, she had gone to the violence against women demonstration. She told us about it on stage, but didn’t stop there. She confessed for the first time: “I too found myself in very difficult situations and had to ask for help. In the end, everything went well for me, but I can't help but empathize with all these women who are victims of femicide.\" She was moved, and I was too.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhich was the most challenging part of it?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThe most challenging part of Vanity Fair Stories today is selecting the people who have a strong community that reaches beyond the screen. Even if our event is live-streamed, it’s essential to fill the theater and to bring readers and potential readers closer, getting to know them and understanding what they appreciate and what they would like differently.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eGuests from different industries, such as music, cinema, entertainment and culture, participated in the event.\u003c/strong\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003cstrong\u003eCould you tell us a little bit about the process on how you planned the programming around this two-day event?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eIt’s essential to start with the biggest names and secure some immediately, and by immediately, I mean at least three or four months before the event. It’s equally necessary to alternate high and low, pop and less pop, in the schedule — the leading characters of the most popular TV series, the stars of cinema, the creators of the catchphrases of the year and the busy singer-songwriters, the hosts who are revolutionizing television and cult writers, comedians and activists. It also helps to break up the rhythm of the panels with different performances, including monologues, performances and music, which is the most popular.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIf you could wish for a celebrity or group to be a part of the event, who would it be?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eMåneskin! I was the first journalist ever to interview them. The day after coming second at X Factor 2017 with the then director of Glamour Cristina Lucchini, we decided that they deserved more space than the winner,Lorenzo Licitra. There were a few days left before Christmas and we quickly organized a photo shoot and a long conversation with all the band members.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eIf I were speaking to them today on the Stories stage, I would show them those images,\u0026nbsp;taken by photographer Giovanni Gastel, who passed from Covid and I would reread some of the answers they had given me. I would start right there to tell their story.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe brand just celebrated its 20th anniversary. What does this event mean for the brand, and how will it continue to evolve in the future?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eVanity Fair Stories is the most important event for the brand, I believe. Among various reasons, it’s the moment in which the editorial team meets readers and audiences. It’s exciting and enriching at the same time. Now in its sixth edition, it’s time for the format to evolve and introduce new elements. This year, for example, we opened the stage to dance performances and the foyer to flash mobs. Who knows what will be next.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eVanity Fair Stories was the third and final act of the magazine's 20th anniversary celebration and a time to reflect on the future ahead. In your opinion, what future lies ahead?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI am convinced that a quality future awaits us, with many cross-media initiatives to embrace new audiences. An example is the fact that next year, for the first time, Vanity Fair Italia will be among the protagonists of the second season of a well-known Italian TV series by Cross Productions and distributed by Prime Video, “Prisma by Ludovico Bessegato” about a very delicate case of revenge porn. The idea was born during the last edition of Vanity Fair Stories, while chatting with him backstage.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","publishedDate":"2023-11-27T00:00:00.000Z","isFeatured":false,"isHidden":false,"tag":null,"createdAt":"2023-11-27T15:02:56.557Z","updatedAt":"2023-11-27T15:03:51.036Z","publishedAt":"2023-11-27T15:03:47.958Z","locale":"en","Image":{"data":{"id":4811,"attributes":{"name":"Untitled design (8).jpg","alternativeText":null,"caption":null,"width":1920,"height":1080,"formats":{"large":{"ext":".jpg","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/large_Untitled_design_8_e1efdc5cd4.jpg","hash":"large_Untitled_design_8_e1efdc5cd4","mime":"image/