3e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTell us a little bit about yourself and your role at GQ.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eOne of the best parts of my job is working on GQ Men of the Year— this is my 9th year curating the talent on the cover and in the issue, as well as the Los Angeles event. Prior to GQ, I had invaluable experiences working on the\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003eTeen Vogue\u0026nbsp;\u003c/i\u003eYoung Hollywood party, the\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003eVanity Fair\u003c/i\u003e Oscar party and the\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003eVogue\u003c/i\u003e Met Ball— all of which I have a lot of nostalgia for.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eWhen I started at GQ in 2015, it was our 20th anniversary of Men of the Year and I felt like the star power was at an all time high. Each year I strive for the talent to reflect the most important cultural moments of the year, and because we are competitive with other media companies’ end of year tentpoles, we have to identify who we want in a timely manner and then secure the exclusive. It’s a fun challenge.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eGiven the brand's global readership, how do you ensure that the talent selected for the MOTY issues have international appeal and relevance, while also reflecting the specific international markets and their own cultural appetites?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI book GQ U.S.’s Men of the Year issue and support the global markets who need help. One crucial part of the booking is event attendance, which is negotiated with the cover or inside story booking. I am hyper-focused on making sure the subjects resonate with the individual markets. I love calling the HECs and bringing them ideas for their movie star or musician and performer. A lot of markets use their music cover to also book their party performance. Some markets will share covers, but we are more interested in celebrating and securing the talent at the events around the world, so we are working with different people.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRoxanne Behr (Global Creative Director):\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTell us a little bit about yourself and your role at GQ.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI am the creative director, where I oversee all photos across GQ’s platforms. I lead a team of extremely talented and hardworking photo editors and creative producers.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCan you share some insight into the creative process behind the Men of the Year issue, from initial concept development to the final execution?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThis was our first year naming our Men of the Year cover stars as party co-hosts, so it was important that the covers felt like a cohesive series. We wanted them to feel like a series of posters as much as magazine covers. Photographer Jack Bridgland is one of the most distinctive creative voices of his generation. His cool, icy studio lighting is so instantly recognizable. We were thrilled he was available to shoot all three covers. While each shoot had its own creative approach (Kim the Boss, Jacob as Yves Saint Laurent, Travis’ pictures were so loud you could hear them), the whole project hangs together as a series.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIn your role, how do you collaborate with other departments such as photography, styling, and editorial, to ensure a cohesive and compelling visual narrative for the Men of the Year issue?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eEvery photo shoot is a deep collaboration between the photo, talent, fashion, and edit teams. I work especially close with the fashion dept, developing the character for our subject and ensuring that the photographer and stylist are creatively aligned. While we are producing, my team coordinates all production details in concert with the talent team, who works with the talent’s publicists.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eJoel Pavelski (Global Director of Content Strategy):\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTell us a little bit about yourself and your role at GQ.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI’m a proud Midwestern farm boy who grew up reading\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003eGQ\u0026nbsp;\u003c/i\u003eand dreaming about New York. After I fell in love with my college newspaper, graduated and moved to the city 13 years ago, I bounced around tabloid newspapers and new media start-ups as a writer and editor before finding a career groove driving digital transformations and running social media and audience development.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eIn my role as the Global Director of Content Strategy for GQ, I work as a close deputy to our Global Editorial Director, Will Welch to manage the editorial teams who make GQ and use my deep understanding of our audience and our business to connect the dots between their creative storytelling and the best ways to reach people on social media, video, email and other platforms. I’m an editor, an operator, a manager, a strategist and, sometimes, a fixer who fills in the gaps wherever we see a need.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow do you approach translating the print edition's creative vision into the digital and social media world?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eFor 28 years, GQ Men of the Year has highlighted the most influential people from across the worlds of fashion, entertainment, and sports in one blowout issue and event. It’s been our biggest programming moment of the year since 1996, but this year, GQ’s Global Editorial Director Will Welch has led the way on a vision to make it even bigger.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eIt all starts with a stunning, insightful, compelling Dec/Jan issue, full of stories that you haven’t heard before—and never would’ve guessed. Our insanely creative and hard-working visual, digital, video and social media teams are surrounding that issue with behind-the-scenes videos, wild digital designs, deep collaboration with our story subjects, and powerful platform-specific storytelling. And we’re innovating with new storytelling formats we’ve never tried before —\u0026nbsp;like our first-ever video cover story, which lets the audience follow along for the first time as one of our greatest writers and a dynamic camera crew create a GQ cover story out of on-the-ground interviews with Andre 3000.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eAll of this culminates at the event in LA, which will be the menswear red carpet event of the year, with a stacked crew of A-listers attending in eye-popping fits, and the most live and most comprehensive coverage we’ve ever attempted across GQ.com and GQ’s social channels, with getting ready videos, red carpet slow-mo, celebrity-hosted interviews, elevated fashion films, and insider looks at what really happens inside a rollicking GQ party.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow do you continue innovating that approach year to year?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThe key is collaboration! And an openness to experimentation. There are a lot of new ideas for ways to bring Men of the Year to our audience that we’re testing out for the first time this year.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStephanie Williams (Global Director, Audience Development):\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTell us a little bit about yourself and your role at GQ.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI'm the global executive director of audience development for GQ, and I'm incredibly lucky and fortunate to oversee our global audience growth strategy and GQ's amazing audience development team located in our 10 markets. Essentially, my job is to help GQ build new audiences and cultivate loyal readers both on and off-platform, using data as a foundation to make strategic decisions. The cool thing about my role is that I get to collaborate with pretty much every department at Condé Nast since our audience team touches every aspect of the business — from product to newsletter to consumer revenue. Since my team works on so many different types of projects, no day is the same, and I appreciate the variety.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow does GQ leverage various social media platforms (Instagram, Twitter, TikTok, etc.) to create a cohesive and integrated promotional campaign for the Men of the Year issue. Are there unique strategies implemented on each platform?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eOur approach is bespoke to each social platform, but the messaging is the same across the board: GQ's Men of the Year party is menswear's biggest red carpet moment that brings together some of the most influential people in entertainment, fashion and sports.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eJoining our Global Editorial Director Will Welch at MOTY, this year are co-hosts Kim Kardashian, Travis Scott, Jacob Elordi and Tom Ford, who we made front and center in our promotional efforts. The social and video teams were able to capture some exclusive content with talent ahead of time that we then used to create some high-energy sizzles that helped articulate the event's vision across our social channels. Notably on Instagram and TikTok where video plays an integral part in driving engagement and reach.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eTikTok and Instagram are a boon for driving awareness to the event and our cover stories, especially with younger audiences who may not be subscribed to our social channels. These two channels have the most engaged audiences by far but those audiences don't really leave the platforms to visit other websites. This is partly because there's not a streamlined way to insert links into posts or find those links, unlike Twitter and Facebook. Facebook and Twitter serve as a vessel to drive traffic to all of our great Men of the Year content but are much more limited in reaching new audiences compared to TikTok and Instagram. We'll share throwback photos of some of the most viral moments from past Men of the Year parties to build anticipation in the week leading up to the event on Instagram and TikTok, and then devote the first half of the week to rolling out our cover stories across all platforms. These rollouts include a mix of exclusive photos and behind-the-scenes videos of the cover shoots, and clips from original video IPs such as 10 Essentials and Iconic Characters.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eDuring the party, we post photos and videos from the red carpet across all our channels, along with any editorial coverage published that night. The momentum goes well beyond the actual night though — we have so much content that we end up rolling everything out over the course of several days.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIn terms of influencer marketing, how does GQ collaborate with celebrity talent and fashion influencers to amplify the reach and impact of the Men of the Year issue and event?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eIt's important that we amplify the event in places that aren't just our O\u0026amp;O because this is a huge opportunity to reach new audiences beyond what we've cultivated. For party coverage this year we've tried something new by inviting a select group of content creators to capture key moments as they happened live to share with their social followers. These creators are closely aligned with our brand vision and offer a unique point of view that's different from the usual party content we do.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eIn the past, we've also shot and produced ‘Get Ready With Me’ videos with talent as they're getting ready to step onto the red carpet, which has also been helpful in amplifying the message. When we shoot bespoke videos with talent we try to do an Instagram collaboration post with them — we've found a lot of success that way with boosting the reach and visibility of our content.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","publishedDate":"2023-11-20T00:00:00.000Z","isFeatured":false,"isHidden":false,"tag":null,"createdAt":"2023-11-20T17:22:34.867Z","updatedAt":"2023-11-20T17:22:38.041Z","publishedAt":"2023-11-20T17:22:38.036Z","locale":"en","Image":{"data":{"id":4799,"attributes":{"name":"Untitled design (8).jpg","alternativeText":null,"caption":null,"width":1920,"height":1080,"formats":{"large":{"ext":".jpg","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/large_Untitled_design_8_67a8da3dcf.jpg","hash":"large_Untitled_design_8_67a8da3dcf","mime":"image/jpeg","name":"large_Untitled design (8).jpg","path":null,"size":52.64,"width":1000,"height":563},"small":{"ext":".jpg","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/small_Untitled_design_8_67a8da3dcf.jpg","hash":"small_Untitled_design_8_67a8da3dcf","mime":"image/jpeg","name":"small_Untitl