om Tulane University.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eTruthfully, I found out about the position because I followed\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003eThem\u003c/i\u003e incessantly since 2017 and would regularly check to see if anything would open. Now, here I am.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow do you describe your job to friends and family?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI always joke to my family that my job is essentially being the overlord of Gay Wikipedia.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eIf you combined WebMD and WikiHow — and made them both incredibly queer — that’s how you end up with the\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003eThem\u003c/i\u003e Answers \u0026amp; Advice section.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eBut in all seriousness, I love being able to put out helpful, tangible information for queer and trans people just trying to get some answers and advice! Afterall, we all should have the ability to participate in one of the most human activities on planet earth: Googling our medical symptoms and woes away to hopefully get some helpful information. If you have a queer question — whether it be transition-related, romantic, sexual, or just about whether or not you’re going to have a bad week as a Taurus — I’ve got you covered.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThis week is Trans Awareness Week, what does this week mean to you?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThis week makes me reflect on the importance of awareness: I know that when I was in the process of coming out, it was truly everyday out trans people on the internet that guided my path and helped me understand myself. Making sure that trans people, particularly trans youth, who are still finding themselves have access to the resources and community they need is something I take very seriously.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eAs an Indigenous trans person (Quechua Qariwarmi), I also think it’s critical that people understand that the visibility and awareness of trans folks we have today is greatly thanks to Black, Indigenous, and broadly POC trans elders who have given their entire lives to the cause of trans liberation.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow do we continue on educating and spreading the message of awareness and support in the community?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI would say listening to trans people and following our guidance is the first step. Most people in the U.S. say they have not met a trans person — this is a huge problem because it can be so easy to not see our humanity if we aren’t conceptually people who can exist in your life. In terms of cis allies looking to do the work, I would start by just familiarising yourself with trans stories. It might seem simple but it can really go a long way. If you don’t know where to start, might I suggest checking out\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.them.us/\"\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003ci\u003e\u003cu\u003eThem\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e?\u003ci\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/i\u003e(Not to shamelessly plug.)\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat is something that currently interests you?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI like to watch TV eras to get a sense of what the media landscape was like in a particular decade. Currently, my focus is the late 2000s and early 2010s, so think\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003eJersey Shore\u003c/i\u003e,\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003eKeeping Up with The Kardashians\u003c/i\u003e, and\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003eGirls\u003c/i\u003e. I’m learning a lot about pop culture and gender during that era.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhen you’re not at work, how do you spend your free time?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eFamously, I used to commute back and forth from Boston every weekend to see my long-distance partner (very queer of me, I know). They moved to NYC earlier this year, so now that I’m not doing that, I have a lot more free time. I generally like to go to queeraoke at The Bush, hang out with my bunny Benito, go to Indigenous Andean community events in the city, and cook a lot of meals.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat is something you wish more people knew about?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI wish more people knew how funny trans people are. I know we’re often the butt of the joke or painted as somehow being sensitive, but I think you have to have the thickest skin on the planet to go to a community event (let’s say Body Hack) knowing three of your exes and two of your crushes will be there. Like that’s actual comedy.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat is your biggest guilty pleasure?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI wouldn’t say I have any guilty pleasures. That being said, my partner and I have deeply different tastes in horror movies — they love a haunted house and I love gore — so I have to save some of my favorites for when I’m alone. When they work night shifts at a local queer bar, I tend to do something called the “Quispe Special.” This entails ordering sushi (two salmon nigiris, three pieces of salmon sashimi, and one masago nigiri to be exact), watching any\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003eHellraiser\u003c/i\u003e movie, and chasing it with two episodes of\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003eSouth Park\u003c/i\u003e.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThe two episodes of South Park are actually as close to a guilty pleasure as I get but as someone writing about trans suffering often, sometimes it’s so nice to just turn off my brain and watch something truly mindless.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIf you could have dinner with anyone dead or alive, who would it be and why?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eOh, this is hard. I think probably Chavela Vargas. Her voice is so haunting and I feel like she formed so much of my understanding of queerness and euphoria at a young age. I’m dying to know more about her relationship with Frida Kahlo, but I’d probably have to be a really good dinner companion to hear about that.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat is your most used emoji and the emoji that represents you today?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eMy most used emoji has to be the sparkle emoji, mainly because I hate anything I say sounding too harsh or serious so adding a little pizazz at the end softens it. And who doesn’t love a little sparkle? In terms of the emoji that actually represents me today, I feel like the big, watery-eyed pouty face really embodies me. I’m feeling sensitive, sincere, and crampy.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","publishedDate":"2023-11-13T00:00:00.000Z","isFeatured":false,"isHidden":false,"tag":null,"createdAt":"2023-11-13T17:02:33.179Z","updatedAt":"2023-11-13T17:02:51.462Z","publishedAt":"2023-11-13T17:02:49.714Z","locale":"en","Image":{"data":{"id":4793,"attributes":{"name":"Screenshot 2023-11-13 at 11.58.18.png","alternativeText":null,"caption":null,"width":922,"height":966,"formats":{"small":{"ext":".png","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/small_Screenshot_2023_11_13_at_11_58_18_0e0eb8e6b0.png","hash":"small_Screenshot_2023_11_13_at_11_58_18_0e0eb8e6b0","mime":"image/png","name":"small_Screenshot 2023-11-13 at 11.58.18.png","path":null,"size":508.89,"width":477,"height":500},"medium":{"ext":".png","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/medium_Screenshot_2023_11_13_at_11_58_18_0e0eb8e6b0.png","hash":"medium_Screenshot_2023_11_13_at_11_58_18_0e0eb8e6b0","mime":"image/png","name":"medium_Screenshot 2023-11-13 at 11.58.18.png","path":null,"size":1107.46,"width":716,"height":750},"thumbnail":{"ext":".png","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/thumbnail_Screenshot_2023_11_13_at_11_58_18_0e0eb8e6b0.png","hash":"thumbnail_Screenshot_2023_11_13_at_11_58_18_0e0eb8e6b0","mime":"image/png","name":"thumbnail_Screenshot 2023-11-13 at 11.58.18.png","path":null,"size":53.55,"width":149,"height":156}},"hash":"Screenshot_2023_11_13_at_11_58_18_0e0eb8e6b0","ext":".png","mime":"image/png","size":520.05,"url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/Screenshot_2023_11_13_at_11_58_18_0e0eb8e6b0.png","previewUrl":null,"provider":"aws-s3","provider_metadata":null,"createdAt":"2023-11-13T17:01:18.247Z","updatedAt":"2023-11-13T17:01:18.247Z"}}},"tags":[]},{"id":4983,"Title":"We Are Condé Nast: Raunaq Raje","SEOTitle":null,"SEODescription":null,"slug":"we-are-conde-nast-raunaq-raje","category":"people","summary":"Condé Nast India’s National Category Head Raunaq Raje shares what Diwali means to him, how he plans to celebrate and what he recommends for your first time in India.","text":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTell us a little bit about yourself. How did you find your way to Condé Nast?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI have always loved stories and I feel deeply connected to a brand when it has a great story to tell. As an engineering and management graduate and then a digital evangelist, I worked for over a decade helping build streaming platforms and working on digital media plans, which never really allowed me to be a part of this beautiful storytelling process.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eSo when a colleague reached out to me with an opportunity to be a part of an organization, which is one of the biggest storytellers in the luxury space, it immediately appealed to my creative spirit and that led me to the doors of Condé Nast.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow do you describe your job to friends and family?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI always tell everyone around me that my job is about collaboration, communication and co-creation.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eCollaborating with talented internal teams and partners, working on interesting campaigns to build a great story for our brands through branded content or events, or co-creating something that redefines culture. There never is a dull day in the office, whether it is working on the next drive project for a motoring brand or crafting a co-branded event for an alcohol major, it is always full of fun and learning.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDiwali is on Sunday November 12. What does the holiday mean to you and how do you plan to celebrate?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eDiwali for me is always the best time of year. It is the festival of food, family and friends. While it is celebrated differently across various regions and cultures in India, for me, it’s all about meeting my family – spending time with them, having a Diwali party, playing cards, putting up ‘\u003ci\u003ekandeels\u003c/i\u003e’ or Indian paper lanterns and of course hogging on delicious varieties of ‘\u003ci\u003eFaraal,’\u003c/i\u003e which is essentially an array of Diwali special sweets and snacks.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat is your favorite part of Diwali celebrations?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThe whiff of homemade snacks, the beautiful melange of colorful\u0026nbsp;\u003ci\u003ekurtas\u003c/i\u003e and festive gowns, the brightly lit night sky, the glittering city lights, the laughter filled living rooms, beautifully decorated corners of home, homecoming of the ones who have left the city for greener pastures, makes this festival truly special. All of these things coming together is my favorite part, which makes Diwali not just a festival but an emotion.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat is something you wish more people knew about Diwali?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eCenturies ago, Diwali was the time when Indians first started a ritual to use a mixture of ayurvedic herbs as a scrub before they took their first bath of the festival called the ‘\u003ci\u003eAbhyanga Snan,’\u003c/i\u003e which means the first bath.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThis was predominantly because Diwali marks the beginning of winter season and these ayurvedic herbs consisting of indigenous ingredients are hugely beneficial to the skin, which can get damaged during the season. While this ritual still continues today in many parts of India, this practice of using these scrubs is now an integral part of offerings in many spas around the world.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYou have been making strides on the commercial team. What are you most proud of so far this year?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI think I am most proud of my team and how they managed to adapt and drive business even during these challenging times. The team has managed to get into the right places and maximize revenue at the same time, delivering value to our partners and advertisers. From designing bespoke sneakers for an Alcobev brand to curating welcome kits for a major international bank, we have done it all.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTell us three things you hope to accomplish next year.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eAchieving fitness goals, learning a new dance form and exploring a new destination.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIf you could give a Ted talk on one thing, what would it be?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eIt is said that the best stories are often found in the pages of your passport. Being an avid traveler and ‘toastmaster’ for over a decade, I love to explore new places, cuisines and cultures. My TED Talk would be on ‘Influencing your personality through travel’ wherein I can talk about my own experiences and share how it changed my perspective and showed me that there is more to aspire to than just your usual ‘work-life’ balance.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIf you could have an unlimited supply of one thing, what would it be and why?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI think without a doubt more time. I love to take on multiple things and I always find myself juggling with time. I would love to have an unlimited supply of time so that I can do everything that I love to do at my own pace.\u0026nbsp; I would also spend more time with my family and friends, travel and pursue hobbies. Then, my life would be almost perfect.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat would you recommend for someone to do for their first time visiting India?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eIndia is beyond the land of spices and the Taj Mahal. There are 28 states and 8 union territories in India and each of these 34 regions have something unique and indigenous to offer.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eFor someone visiting India for the first time, I would definitely suggest visiting one of these regions and experience the food, culture and various joints like a local. Try the local markets and local neighborhoods where you can see the true Indian culture – from local grocery stores, rundown eateries or watching a gully cricket match. That is where the true essence of India lies.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","publishedDate":"2023-11-06T00:00:00.000Z","isFeatured":false,"isHidden":false,"tag":null,"createdAt":"2023-11-06T14:24:30.489Z","updatedAt":"2023-11-06T14:24:39.672Z","publishedAt":"2023-11-06T14:24:39.144Z","locale":"en","Image":{"data":{"id":4766,"attributes":{"name":"Screenshot 2023-11-06 at 13.55.27.png","alternativeText":null,"caption":null,"width":964,"height":870,"formats":{"small":{"ext":".png","url":"https://strapi-bus-eng-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/small_Screenshot_2023_11_06_at_13_55_27_7458260ac9.png","hash":"small_Screenshot_2023_11_06_at_13_55_27_7458260ac9","mime":"image/png","name":"small_Screenshot 2023-11-06 at 13.55.27.png","path":null,"size":62