Editor Anna Lagos shares what Hispanic Heritage Month means to her, what she looks forward to most at the WIRED en Español summit and some of the greatest technological advancements.","text":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTell us a little bit about yourself. How did you find your way to Condé Nast?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eI studied Communication and later delved into Spanish literature, and sooner rather than later, I fell in love with written journalism. I have collaborated with media outlets such as Reforma, Terra, ElEconomista.es, and Entrepreneur. Before joining WIRED, I worked for about 6 years as the Head of Social Media for the newspaper EL PAÍS for Latin America. In addition, I wrote dozens of journalistic articles for the Culture, Society, Environment, and Technology sections of EL PAÍS.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eIn addition, I have a Master's degree in Marketing and Advertising. I'm an enthusiast of good stories, especially if they're related to the Environment, Archaeology, Science, or Technology, of course. I'm interested in giving visibility to projects and figures from Latin America; they are tireless warriors who are changing the world for the better.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow do you describe your job to friends and family?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eWork? I'm fortunate to do what I love most in life at WIRED, so my job is attending meetings (Is my boss reading this?)\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThis month is Hispanic Heritage Month. What does it mean to you?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eThis holds great significance for me. My mother's family, starting with my grandmother, migrated to the United States over three decades ago. There, they found opportunities that weren't available in Mexico, and at the same time, they have contributed to the country in various ways. The undeniable strength of Latinos in the United States convinces me that the fusion of our perspectives adds value and enriches us continuously.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYou love topics related to the environment, science and technology. What is something that you learned recently that fascinated you?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eI recently interviewed Pati Ruiz Corzo, who succeeded in designating approximately 385,000 hectares of Mexico's Sierra Gorda in the state of Querétaro as a biosphere reserve—an untouched territory. This paradise combines all of Mexico's ecosystems except marine ones. \"The Sierra Gorda is a cosmic library,\" she told me in an interview with \u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://es.wired.com/articulos/pati-ruiz-corzo-la-guardiana-de-la-reserva-de-la-biosfera-de-la-sierra-gorda-de-queretaro\"\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#1155cc;\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eWIRED en Español.\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eNow at 70 years old, she looks back with a smile on how she left her position as the first violinist in the Querétaro City Chamber Orchestra at 30 to seek a simpler life in a rural mountain community in Jalpan de Serra, at the heart of Mexico, the last well-preserved area in the country's centre. The Sierra Gorda, declared a protected natural area in 1997, stands as Mexico's only one of its kind, thanks to the dedication of committed individuals. It's a living example of how community-led movements can aid in safeguarding and restoring endangered ecosystems.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat is your favorite book that you have read in the past month? Why?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eI'm captivated by \u003ci\u003eUn verdor terrible\u003c/i\u003e by Benjamín Labatut. It's an essay on science transformed into literature. The Chilean author delves into topics like the first modern synthetic pigment, Prussian blue, created in the 18th century by an alchemist seeking the Elixir of Life through cruel experiments on living animals. This pigment later becomes the origin of hydrogen cyanide, a deadly gas that German-Jewish chemist Fritz Haber, the father of chemical warfare, used to develop the pesticide Zyklon. Unknowingly, this gas would be utilized by the Nazis in extermination camps to murder members of their own family.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eThe book explores mathematical explorations of Alexander Grothendieck, leading him to mystical delirium, social isolation, and madness. It touches upon a letter sent to Einstein by a dying friend from the trenches of World War I, containing the solution to the equations of relativity and the earliest prediction of black holes. It also delves into the rivalry between the two founders of quantum mechanics—Erwin Schrödinger and Werner Heisenberg. An absolute marvel.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWIRED en Español Summit returns this year on September 21. What are you looking forward to most?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eWe have exceptional guests at the WIRED Summit. The panel I'm most looking forward to is the one we've titled: 'Latin America Embarks on Space Travel: Projects and Protagonists,' featuring: Gustavo Medina, head of the LINX laboratory that developed the Beehive Project, in which five lightweight, cost-effective mini-robots with self-organising capabilities are aiming to reach the Moon; Guillermo Chin Canché, a Mexican scientist of Mayan origin and a doctoral candidate in Physical Oceanography, who is working on NASA's Dragonfly mission; and Katya Echazarreta, the first Mexican woman to travel to space, who has temporarily paused her NASA career to advocate for accelerating the aerospace industry in Mexico.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYou were recently \u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eselected for MasterLAB, a training program by Quinto Elemento Lab. Tell us a little bit more about this program and its initiative.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;\"\u003eI was selected for MasterLAB, a training program by \u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://quintoelab.org/nosotros\"\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:#ffffff;color:#1155cc;\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eQuinto Elemento Lab\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;\"\u003e for editors in the planning and execution of major investigative reports. MasterLab 2023 brings together the best editors from the continent and offers personalised mentorship from experienced journalists in investigative editing. The program has selected 20 journalists from across the continent to provide them with the necessary tools to conceive, organise, narrate, and produce powerful stories, while keeping their teams safe. I am proudly a part of the third generation of MasterLAB.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:#ffffff;color:#222222;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIn your opinion, what are some of the greatest technological achievements?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eInternet, quantum physics, the discovery of the CRISPR-Cas9 gene-editing technique, it has the potential to revolutionise medicine and agriculture by allowing precise manipulation of DNA. (And…air conditioning!)\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhen you are not learning and reporting on technology and science, what do you like to do in your free time?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eI love going to the forest; it's my favorite place. I enjoy short trips, visiting museums, and learning about almost anything. I also love engaging in conversations and reading peacefully.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e","publishedDate":"2023-09-18T11:00:00.000Z","isFeatured":false,"isHidden":false,"tag":null,"createdAt":"2023-10-09T02:14:52.679Z","updatedAt":"2023-10-09T02:14:56.445Z","publishedAt":"2023-09-18T14:22:10.938Z","locale":"en","Image":{