-are-conde-nast-giles-hattersley","category":"people","summary":"Vogue’s European Features Director Giles Hattersley discusses Vogue World: London, donating to performing art organizations and what he is looking forward to most at the event.","text":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTell us a little bit about yourself. How did you find your way to Condé Nast?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eI joined Condé Nast in 2017 on the same morning as Edward Enninful, then British Vogue’s newly arrived Editor-in-Chief. I had a ‘first day at highschool’ feeling about it all if memory serves.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow do you describe your job to friends and family?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eI adore my family and friends for many reasons, including the fact that they are healthily non-fascinated by the minutiae of my job. I’m not 100% sure most of them know what an average day looks like for me. We tend to talk more about culture or the news, with just the right amount of gossip tossed in for good measure. I highly recommend this as a life strategy.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eVogue World will be in London this year on September 14. Can you tell us what your role was in creating this event?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eVogue World: London is the definition of team effort, and it’s been exciting supporting Edward, Anna and Mark Guiducci on some of the elements. I’ve enjoyed being a sounding board and fixer on some of the political, cultural and talent elements. At the end of the day, it’s all about making magic happen in a way only Vogue can. I’m especially proud of the philanthropic push that will ensure a legacy is in place that uplifts London’s creativity beyond the dazzle of the night itself.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:#ffffff;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e100% of net ticket proceeds from Vogue World: London will benefit performing arts organizations large and small in the U.K., including the National Theatre, Royal Opera House including the Royal Ballet, Southbank Sinfonia and the dance company Rambert. What was it like working with these organizations?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eSome of the amazing organizations we have worked with have contributed to the night itself, with fantastic creatives from the National Theatre, Rambert and more creating work that will appear on stage. It’s really thrilling to be able to support those organizations in return with meaningful donations that will ensure they are able to continue staging their world class work at such a fragile time for the U.K. arts scene. But we wanted to go further, and Anna and Edward put together a steering committee and we worked closely with some of London’s most prominent performing arts leaders and the GLA to select a host of small to micro-sized charities who work across the worlds of dance, opera, live music, theatre and mixed disciplines, and are geographically spread across the capital, with an emphasis on uplifting marginalised voices and the arts. It was an honor to be a part of the process.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow will the ticket proceeds affect and benefit these organizations?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eOne of the exciting elements – especially when dealing with charities with very small turnovers – is being able to make funds available with limited strings attached. To a small dance troop or community theatre org, the sort of funding Vogue World is providing might be a means of survival. For some it will mean logistical support in terms of overheads and staffing, for others it will mean being able to initiate a new program to support young writers. We’re excited to keep in touch with all our beneficiaries and spotlight lots of their important work in the coming months.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat are you most looking forward to at Vogue World: London?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eWell I hope I get to see everyone – from superstars to supermodels to arts students – enjoy it. And I hope I get a moment to take it all in myself!\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAll eyes will be on London for this incredible event, but for those visiting the city what do you recommend doing/visiting with some downtime?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eHave dinner at Sessions Arts Club, go and see The Effect at the National and be sure to take a walk though Regents Park in some early autumn cashmere as a new season beckons.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow will you relax when Vogue World is done?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eRelax? Don’t be silly. What’s next!\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhich is your favorite story to appear in British Vogue this year, or you think is an unmissable read we should all catch up on?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003eToo many to mention, but I thought writer Zing Tsjeng did a beautiful job profiling \u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.vogue.com/article/zadie-smith-the-fraud-september-2023\"\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#1155cc;\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eZadie Smith\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e for our September issue and Frances Ryan absolutely nailed her interview with \u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/selma-blair-british-vogue-interview\"\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#1155cc;\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eSelma Blair\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e for May. I’m especially proud of our \u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/vogue-disability-portfolio-2023\"\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#1155cc;\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eDisability\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;\"\u003e and \u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/british-vogue-july-2023-pride-cover\"\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#1155cc;\"\u003e\u0